06937nam a22009615i 9780824840365DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029816916  a(OCoLC)1032676181  a(OCoLC)1037979828  a(OCoLC)1041996973  a(OCoLC)1046614174  a(OCoLC)1047016795  a(OCoLC)1049676552  a(OCoLC)1054879245  a97808248403657 a10.1515/97808248403652doi  a(DE-B1597)484605  a(OCoLC)1013954438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aD16.25b.I527 2005 7aHIS0370002bisacsh04a90122200aInteractions :bTransregional Perspectives on World History /ced. by Jerry H. Bentley, Anand A. Yang, Renate Bridenthal. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (256 p.) :billus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Regional Histories, Global Processes, Cross-Cultural Interactions -- t2. From Archaic Globalization to International Networks, circa 1600–2000 -- t3. Sufi Brotherhoods: Transcultural /Transstate Networks in the Muslim World -- t4. Cotton: A Global History -- t5. From Red Crosses to Golden Arches: China, the Red Cross, and The Hague Peace Conference, 1899–1900 -- t6. Constructing Africa: African American Writers before Emancipation -- t7. Migration Control and the Globalization of Borders: China and the United States, 1898–1911 -- t8. Smuggling and Its Malcontents -- t9. Cartographies of Connection: Ocean Maps as Metaphors for Interarea History -- t10. Chronology, Crossroads, and Commonwealths: World-Regional Schemes and the Lessons of Caucasia -- t11. Regimes of World Order: Global Integration and the Production of Difference in Twentieth-Century World History -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays presented here reflect recent widespread interest in reconsidering the political, geographical, and cultural boundaries conventionally observed by area specialists and others. They intentionally range widely through time and space, dealing with diverse issues and contexts, but each highlights the very general theme of cross-cultural interaction. Although they draw heavily on area studies, the contributors seek to put previously separate bodies of scholarship in dialogue with one another by exploring those interactions that have historically linked world regions.Four general themes are especially prominent in this volume, and the essays develop sophisticated positions on each. On the issue of agency and structure, they offer useful guidance toward recognizing the importance of both human agency and historical structures in historical processes. On the theme of states and their roles in cross-cultural interactions, they acknowledge that states do not entirely control their own destinies but nevertheless deeply influence the development of these exchanges, sometimes decisively so. Regarding the theme of the global and the local, they emphasize the reciprocal influence of global dynamics and local circumstances and agree that analyses must take both into account to be successful. Finally, all of the essays allow that the theme of cross-cultural interaction is crucial to understanding the world and its development through time.Contributors:C. A. Bayly; Sven Beckert; Jerry H. Bentley; Renate Bridenthal; Charles Bright; Michael Geyer; Alan L. Karras; Adam McKeown; Colin Palmer; Stephen H. Rapp, Jr.; Caroline Reeves; John O. Voll; Kären Wigen; Anand A. Yang.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArea studiesvCongresses. 0aIntercultural communicationvCase studiesvCongresses. 0aIntercultural communicationvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aBayly, C. A., econtribut